    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>see <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.22.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">15.22.2 of the JLS</a>.  For boolean operands, the <code>&amp;</code> operator is boolean, not bitwise.  The only difference between <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>&amp;</code> for boolean operands is that for <code>&amp;&amp;</code> it is short circuited (meaning that the second operand isn't evaluated if the first operand evaluates to false).</p>\n\n<p>So in your case, if <code>b</code> is a primitive, <code>a = a &amp;&amp; b</code>, <code>a = a &amp; b</code>, and <code>a &amp;= b</code> all do the same thing.</p>\n"
  }, {
